  "original_title": "OPV P 627 Navy\u2019s latest addition sails for Colombo from Seattle",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "OPV P 627 Navy\u2019s latest addition sails for Colombo from Seattle",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "COLOMBO (News 1st); The Offshore Patrol Vessel P 627, which was formally handed over to the Sri Lanka Navy by the U.S. Coast Guard in October 2021, departed for Sri Lanka from the Port of Seattle, United States on 03rd September 2022. The homebound journey began, after the modernization work of the ship to suit the operational needs of the Sri Lanka Navy.",
        "Sri Lanka Navy officially took delivery of the EX-United States Coast Guard Cutter, USCGC Douglas Munro, provided by the United States, on 26th October 2021.",
        "Subsequently, she was designated with the Pennant Number P 627 in SLN Fleet and is scheduled to be commissioned with a particular ship name, after her arrival in Sri Lanka. Ex-USCGC Douglas Munro, the second \u2018Hamilton Class High Endurance Cutter\u2019, received by the SLN measures 115m in length, capable of attaining a maximum speed of 29 knots and endurance of 14000 NM at cruising speed. Further, she has been designed for 187 of the crew and is equipped with state-of-the-art weapons and machinery.",
        "Upon official taking over of the ship, she underwent certain modernization with devices and equipment, to suit the operational needs of the Sri Lanka Navy.",
        "Intending to join her home port, P 627, led by the OPVSri Lanka Navy crew, set sail from the Port of Seattle at 0900hrs on 03rd September 2022.",
        "After a long sea voyage spanning about 02 months, P 627 is expected to arrive at the Port of Colombo in the first week of November 2022 and during the passage from Seattle to Colombo she will make port calls at Honolulu in Hawaii, Apra in Guam, United States, Manila in Philippine and Changi in Singapore for replenishment and services.",
        "In the same vein, SLN received SLNS Samudura (P 621) and Gajabahu (P 626) the Offshore Patrol Vessels from the U.S. Coast Guard on previous occasions with a view to strengthening and developing partnerships to overcome common maritime challenges at sea. The delivery of P 627 will also be a symbol of further consolidation of such partnerships and camaraderie.",
        "OPV P 627 Navy\u2019s latest addition sails for Colombo from Seattle"
      ],
